There may come a time after your divorce when you no longer want some of the things [hereinafter called "stuff"] you received in your property division.  The reasons may vary from no longer needing it, or wanting it nor do your kids want your stuff.  Maybe the stuff reminds you of the Ex.  Finally, your tastes may have changed. In the words of <a href="http://tidyingup.com/">Marie Kondo</a>, you may want to keep only the things that "spark your joy" You can now honor your true style and not pretend to love his stuff.

Here are suggestions for dealing with the "stuff:"

The<a href="http://www.hoursinfo.com/salvation-army/chicago/4835429/"> Salvation Army Store </a><a href="http://www.hoursinfo.com/salvation-army/chicago/4835429/">o</a>n Clybourn

This store is clean, spacious and bright. Best for books, clothing, kitchen stuff, ceramics, inexpensive artwork  [Note: check with your tax pro on the requirements for donating items whose value is more than $250.] The Salvation Army is a great organization that helps many folks learn job skills. Lots of parking.

<a title="Ebay" href="http://ebay.com">EBay</a>

Using <a title="ebay" href="http://anywhere.ebay.com/mobile/">Ebay </a>is so easy now that you can do the whole process from any smart phone. Just download the app and your are ready to start!  You can take photos and create listings without ever going to your computer.  I have sold costume jewelry, ceramics, glassware, china and clothing using Ebay.  Pair this with a great service,<a href="https://www.shyp.com/?utm_source=Google&amp;utm_medium=paid_search&amp;utm_campaign=branded_keywords&amp;gclid=CKOyvtTd8soCFQKTaQodh80Exw"> Shyp,</a> to pick up, pack and mail your sold items for the cost of shipping plus $5.00 for the pick up.  Think of all the effort and time you save by using this service!

<strong>Auction houses</strong>

A good place to sell higher end paintings and furniture.  Think <strong><a href="http://www.lesliehindman.com/">Leslie Hindman.</a> </strong>There are other auction houses in town, but this is the best one.  Be sure you understand all the costs and fees involved.

<strong>Shelters for abused and homeless women</strong>

Donate to a charity for homeless women.  One example is  <a title="The Greenhouse" href="http://cawc.org/programs/greenhouse/">The Greenhouse  Shelter,</a> a program of <em>Connections for Abused Women and their Children</em>, is Chicago’s oldest program for victims of domestic violence. Full to capacity 365 days a year, Greenhouse served 234 women and children in 2014. To help meet the daily living needs of those women and children, a list of donations is found <a href="http://cawc.org/support-cawc/wishlist/">here</a> and all items are greatly appreciated!

Another service that is helpful for moving big items is <a title="Dolly" href="https://dolly.com/">Dolly.</a> Download app, use it to get a quote and then move your stuff!

<strong>Downsizing and Donating After Your Divorce? Done!</strong>

In the end, you will feel better, lighter! You will have helped others. Please add your comments for other places that you recommend for moving on the "stuff."

