<img class="s-access-image cfMarker alignright" alt="Product Details" src="http://ecx.images-amazon.com/images/I/51JSjHAMTCL._AA160_.jpg" width="160" height="160" />

Are the  court battles never ending?  Does he/she refuse to  settle?  Does he/she refuse to follow court orders?

Today's <em>New York Time</em>'s <strong>Well Book Club</strong> <a href="http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/projects/book-club/will-i-ever-be-free-of-you/is-my-partner-a-narcissist"> blog</a> has posted a book review, that is so on target:

<em><a href="http://www.amazon.com/Will-Ever-Free-You-High-Conflict/dp/1476755698/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1440444160&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=will+i+ever+be+free+of+you">Will I Ever Be Free of You? How to Navigate a High-Conflict Divorce from a Narcissist and Heal Your Family</a>,</em> authored by Karyl McBride.

<a href="http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/author/tara-parker-pope/">Tara Parker-Pope</a> is the author of the <a href="http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/08/24/divorcing-a-narcissist/?nlid=56766463">blog.</a>

Judges and lawyers rarely talk about the role of personality disorders in high-conflict divorces.  Today there are many blogs, mostly written by women,  who do talk about this issue and share  their experiences and offer support.  It is time that this topic  come out of the blog shadows into mainstream media.

