Tonight's Monthly Blogapalooza-Hour Challenge:

<strong>Write about a time you lost your temper or somebody lost their temper at you</strong>

<strong>Divorcing his temper tantrums</strong>

Wow! This a a great topic and so on point if you have or are going through a divorce!

Growing up, I rarely saw anyone throwing a temper tantrum.  My parents, and my extended family,  which consisted of six sets of aunts and uncles plus 30+ cousins,  dealt with their disappointments and frustrations in very passive ways: ignoring each other, complaining to others, and drinking too much.  No one ever yelled at me or  my seven siblings.  Our house was loud and boisterous but in a lively and happy way. Our German-Irish family adhered to Emily Post's rules of etiquette and seldom reacted in a way to make a scene and embarrass in public.  It was not a perfect childhood [see this post about<a title="A Childhood Fondly Remembered" href="http://www.chicagonow.com/divorce-chicago-style/2014/12/a-childhood-fondly-remembered/"> my childhood</a>] but it was  good enough.

So then.... I met the man who was to be my husband [and the father of my three fabulous children----thank you very much,  D!].

He had an anger issue.

If he were a speedometer on a car, he was permanently stuck in the 60 to 100 mph range. Always angry!

Who knows why as he was good looking, rich, handsome, smart, and very accomplished.

Still, his angry outbursts would yank the rug from under my feet.

I felt that I was always walking on eggshells.

And it was always MY fault.

So, how did I deal with his frequent and unpredictable anger?

After years of not being able to make him happy, I divorced him.

So now, he should be happy, you would think?

And  has no more anger issues?

NOT!!

