There are hundreds, if not thousands, of blogs about divorce, but I like these the best at the moment.  Maybe you would like to write a blog?

Although the divorce process  in every state is similar, every story is different.  Share yours either here or on your own blog. See below for my contact details.

<a title="Chump Lady" href="http://http://www.chumplady.com/">ChumpLady</a>

Are you going through a divorce because your spouse cheated on you? Well, you are not alone.  At this blog you can read some of the stupid things cheaters do.  <strong>The ChumpLady</strong> tells it like it is and minces no words in giving advice. She uses the F*** word often! Be forewarned! The advice here will make you laugh!

<a title="Divorced Moms" href="http://https://www.google.com/search?rls=aso&amp;client=gmail&amp;q=one%20girl%20smiling#rls=aso&amp;q=divorced+moms.com">Divorced Moms Inc</a>

An online  community for divorced women.  This entry ignores my guidelines above in that it is more than just one blog.  It has a whole section of blogs including one clever one,   <a href="http://divorcedmoms.com/blogs/this-cuckoos-nest">This Cuckoos Nes</a>t,  referring to the infrequent custody arrangement when children stay in place and the parents move in and out.

<a title="Divorced Girl Smiling" href="http://divorcedgirlsmiling.com">DivorcedGirlSmilingDivorce Blog </a>

Jackie Pilossoph's divorce blog offers support for women and men.  She has also authored several books [<a href="http://http://www.amazon.com/Divorced-Girl-Smiling-Jackie-Pilossoph/dp/1490463763">Divorced Girl Smiling]</a> and kudos to her as she  has managed to turn her divorce experiences into something positive, and profitable!

<a title="Better After 50" href="http://betterafter50.com/">Better After 50 </a>

Online advice for women going through divorce in mid-life. And we need lots of it.  The title is true: life after divorce after 50 is better!

<a href="http://http://www.lisaescott.com/blog">Lisa E Scott"s Blog</a>

Lisa's blog is about recovering from being in a relationship with a narcissist. If you are divorcing a narcissist or just breaking up with one, you need this advice.  She has written books, including <a href="http://http://www.amazon.com/Path-Forward-Surviving-Narcissist/dp/0985832703/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1433179590&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=the+path+forward">The Path Forward</a>, and<a href="http://http://www.amazon.com/Its-All-About-Him-Narcissist/dp/1599552183/ref=sr_1_2?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1433179675&amp;sr=1-2&amp;keywords=its+all+about+him"> It is All About Him.</a>

<a href="http://https://onemomsbattle.com/">One Moms Battle</a>

Tina battled on her own  without a lawyer [mostly] to get full custody of her two daughters in Texas.  Her former husband is a diagnosed narcissist and was not a responsible parent in any way.  After about three years, the court agreed with her and full custody was awarded with supervised visitation by the father.  The father has not chosen to see those daughters since then.

Although Tina's battle is over, the blog continues with <a href="http://https://onemomsbattle.com/category/lucy-k-wright/">Lucy's story</a>, another example of what it is like to divorce a narcissist.  Very well written.  It makes you want to reach out and do something to not only her former spouse, but to the judge or judges who let this go on and on.

The website for the blog also has a good list of <a href="http://https://onemomsbattle.com/resources-for-npd-sociopaths-or-high-conflict-divorce/">resources</a> while divorcing a narcissist. Tina has several <a href="http://https://onemomsbattle.com/divorcing+a+narcissist+">books</a>, offers divorce coaching and more.  Kudos to her for making her struggle public and making efforts to change the family court system.  Unfortunately, family courts are state creatures and reforms will have to be at the state level.  However education and awareness of the inadequacies and issues of the system as a whole will go a long way towards that goal.

Do you have any helpful blogs that offer either advice or humor to add to this list?

I can be reached at divorcechicagostyle@gmail.com.

