Tonight's challenge here at <em><strong>ChicagoNow</strong></em> is to write about a favorite childhood memory. I grew up in a  family with seven siblings and numerous types of pets, ranging from a pony, snakes, sheep, dogs and  frogs, to name a few, and  there are so many wonderful times to remember.  Whenever we all get together today, which is often, we joke and tell the stories of  our growing up in such wild and crazy family.  We hand down the stories to the grandchildren at various gatherings, by creating trivia contests about who did this or that. For example, who rode  the pony bareback and got kicked off, or who organized an impromptu fire drill one night while it was snowing.

My parents, who are no longer living, were both wonderful,  each in their unique way.  My mother was thrifty and had a good eye for clever finds.  She shopped thrift stores before it was fashionable.  One of her best finds was a lovely wool kilt.  I wore it for years and years.   At Christmas time, each of us received one of her "garage sale" gifts wrapped in the Sunday comics and tied with red ric-rac ribbon. I will never forget that my first apartment was furnished with items she found at the Salvation Army or Goodwill. Incredibly,  I still have most of them!  Our clothes were traded with aunts who had almost  as many children, but whose ages differed by a year or two from us.  Each of my five brothers always had a navy blazer and khaki pants no matter what their size.

My father was eccentric in a [mostly] loveable way.  He drove around in our upscale suburb with the car windows closed in the summer so that neighbors thought he was driving an air-conditioned car--which it wasn't.  He also bought six sheep to keep our three acres looking like he had mowed them  Think how folks in Winnetka would appreciate that and you get an idea of how this was received by some of our very posh neighbors.  Dad also bought a vintage fire truck, which we rode around in all summer.  He lent it to the church parish for the annual carnival.  No seat belts and an open back with two benches!  Wow, we were lucky!

Summers were the highlight of my childhood memories. Days and evenings were spent outside playing with the neighbor children.  We came home for dinner when my father whistled for us.  We ate dinner every night together with my father serving us--the youngest to the oldest [me]. If  we wanted to talk, we had to raise our hand.  We all had chores--the girls did the inside work and the boys did the outside work, which meant that the boys only worked in the warm weather.

If we got into trouble, the punishments included writing out a statement  many times, like, <em>I will not hit my sister, </em>50 times<em>.</em>  Once we  tried to use carbon paper, but if caught, the punishment was doubled.  The other punishment was to walk to or from school which was  about a mile away.

But all was not perfect and  my parents divorced when I was in college. My mother lived the rest of her life very frugally, so much so that the only inheritance I got was from her.  My father ultimately remarried. When he died on Christmas Day in 2006, his second wife litigated against his estate.  My siblings and I had to contribute to the legal fees for that.  I call this an "out-heritance."

In spite of our 12 year age span, we are still great friends,  visiting each other duirng the year, traveling together, taking care of each other and giving advice to respective neices and nephews. We value our connections even more than we did when we were growing up.  One of  my siblings is disabled and we work together as a team to care for him.

In July 2015, we have planned a reunion.   Every sibling, spouse and almost every grandchild and [now one] great grand child will be there! I hope that this event will be one of the fond  childhood memories for the next generation.

