There are many reasons why someone [mostly the woman] cannot file for a divorce.  It can be because the family has few assets.  In that case, if  the income is low enough, there are legal clinics to help---if you can get in to them.

Or,  it is because the moneyed spouse [usually the husband] has control of the assets and funds and will not give the wife the funds she needs to hire a lawyer.

In the second situation, the Illinois divorce laws provide some help for the spouse who does not have access to the marital funds in a series of laws usually termed  "leveling the playing field amendments."  However, these provision do not go far enough [IMHO].  Many an abused or miserable spouse cannot get a divorce because she/he  lack funds for even a retainer.

I have never seen a case where the less moneyed spouse got anything close to 100% of his or her fees paid for by the spouse that controls all the money.  [Note to divorce lawyers reading this:  if you know of a case that does awared most fees to one spouse, please write to me.] The attorney fee issue in divorce is a complicated and an ever shifting area in the law [by virtue of the appellate cases]. Fees can be awarded in pre-decree cases or in post-decree cases [for modification or change in custody issues, for example].  And in a few instances, awarding fees is mandated.

If you want to read a 2014  article about this issue, written by a well-known divorce pratictioner, <a href="http://www.gitlinlawfirm.com/documents/AttorneysFeesinDivorceCasesIllinois1.pdf">read this article.</a>

<strong><a href="http://fundedjustice.com">FundedJustice:</a> Crowd funding for legal causes</strong>

But now there is help:  <a href="http://fundedjustice.com">FundedJustice </a>is crowd funding for legal causes.  Think Kickstarter for your divorce.  <a href="http://fundedjustice.com"><strong>FundedJustice</strong> </a>was launched by a fellow blogger here at <strong><em>ChicagoNow,</em></strong> Michael Helmand, who writes the blog, "Chicago Real Law Blog."

You can read the entire post, <em><strong>Chicago's Real Law Blog: Paying for a lawyer, the one problem I couldn’t solve. Until now.</strong></em> <strong><a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/chicagos-real-law-blog/2014/12/paying-for-a-lawyer-the-one-problem-i-couldnt-solve-until-now/">here.</a></strong>

At this writing, there are few funding campaigns and no divorce campaigns.  So if you know someone who could use this service, please pass this along to them.  Being one of the first to create a campaign will be an advantage. There is a detailed FAQ on getting started.

Thank you, Michael, for doing this! It is bound to change many people's lives. A holiday gift for many!

