My nomination for a new holiday is "<strong>Divorce Day Remembrance"</strong>.

Why? No one gets married to get divorced, right?  But when divorce comes your way, it is painful beyond words.  It tears you up and re-orders your world.  It makes you doubt who you are.  It is a singularly devastating event. Why not recognize this by noting the day of the divorce decree as your "<strong>Divorce Day Remembrance".</strong>  Yes, most of us would prefer to forget these painful times, yet unless you are clueless, you certainly have learned a great deal  and grown as a human being.  So why remember?  Because when we remember our past, we are less likely to repeat our mistakes in the future.

Married folk have wedding anniversaries, a time when a couple recalls the happy events surrounding their wedding. A time to remember and celebrate why they got married and have stayed together through thick and thin.

<strong>Reflections on "Divorce Day Remembrance"</strong>

<strong>"Divorce Day Remembrance"</strong> would be the day that you reflect back on the marriage that failed.  But the reflections should not be just negative.  Remember why you married and why you divorced.  What lessons have you learned?  And has your next relationship been better for the lessons learned from the prior marriage?

Now what if you have had more than one divorce?  Ok, so   you can have more than one <strong>Divorce Day Remembrance</strong>.  Sometimes it takes several tries to get it right.....and if one is lucky to have had more than one love in their life, so much the better.   As the saying goes, "if at first you don't succeed, try, try again."

We are only human.  We marry because we are optimistic that love will prevail.  And when it doesn't,  it does not mean that you have failed.  No, if you can remember what was good about that marriage and what was not good and take those lessons with you for the next relationship, then you win.

Hence, your "<strong>Divorce Day Remembrance"</strong>  will keep you on your path to achieving lasting love and success in your future relationships!

My "<strong>Divorce Day Rembrance"</strong> is September 21.

